    bio: "Zheng He was born Ma He into a Muslim Hui family in Yunnan province during the waning years of the Mongol Yuan dynasty. When Ming forces conquered Yunnan in 1381, the ten-year-old boy was captured, castrated, and placed in the household of Zhu Di, the Prince of Yan. He proved an exceptionally capable and loyal servant, and when Zhu Di seized the imperial throne in 1402 as the Yongle Emperor, Ma He — now renamed Zheng He — was elevated to the rank of Grand Eunuch and entrusted with an unprecedented mission: commanding a vast fleet to project Ming power across the seas.\n\nBetween 1405 and 1433, Zheng He led seven massive maritime expeditions across the South China Sea, the Indian Ocean, the Persian Gulf, and the East African coast. His treasure fleets were staggering in scale, with some voyages reportedly involving over 300 ships and 27,000 men, dwarfing anything Europeans would assemble for another century. The largest vessels, the so-called treasure ships, may have exceeded 100 meters in length — a claim still debated by historians. Zheng He's fleets traded silk, porcelain, and lacquerware for spices, gems, exotic animals, and diplomatic goodwill, establishing or reinforcing tributary relationships with dozens of kingdoms from Java to Mogadishu.\n\nZheng He died during or shortly after his seventh voyage in 1433, and within decades the Ming court turned inward, dismantling the fleet and suppressing records of the expeditions. For centuries his achievements were largely forgotten in China itself. Modern scholarship and rising Chinese national pride have restored Zheng He to prominence as one of history's greatest navigators — a Muslim eunuch who commanded the largest wooden fleet the world has ever seen and connected the civilizations of Asia and Africa decades before European ships rounded the Cape of Good Hope."
